We see that a mere denial of the nexus lands us in a contradiction connected with the antecedent; whereas its admission grants the contradiction which its consequent contains. This dialectical puzzle, as is well known, dates from very early times. In the days of the Greek sophists it took a form somewhat like this: A certain philosopher said that all Cretans were liars; but he was a Cretan himself: did he lie, or did he not lie?
